<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900702-0011</DOCNO><DOCID>900702-0011.</DOCID><HL>   Norway Oil Workers Strike   As Last-Minute Talks Fail   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/02/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   EUROP LABOR</CO><IN>PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><LP>   OSLO -- Striking oil workers began shutting down Norway'soffshore petroleum production after last-minute talks failedto settle on a new contract, the union said.   The Norwegian Federation of Oil Workers said the strikecould be a long one, but didn't estimate when the strikemight end.</LP><TEXT>   Norway's North Sea fields produced 1.63 million barrels aday of oil and 1.8 billion cubic meters of natural gas amonth in April, the latest official figures available. Norwayand the U.K. are Europe's largest petroleum producers.   The government has urged both sides to continuenegotiations, noting that roughly 25% of Norway's nationalincome comes from petroleum, and &quot;a strike could be grave forour economy,&quot; a government spokesman said.   The union said the 2.5% pay raise offered to offshoreworkers is less than half its demand. The union also said thestrike defends workers' negotiation rights and protestsincreased automation that may cost jobs.   Management maintains that the union's average annual wage,313,000 kroner ($48,700), is already 85% higher than theaverage wage in mainland industry.</TEXT></DOC>